DRAFT SECTION IN THE ARMY ACT.

The Hay-Chamberlain army bill was signed by
the President on June 3, 1916. On August 25th
Representative George Huddleston of Alabama in-
troduced a resolution to repeal the section of the
bill which provides for conscription. The section
is as follows:

"‘If for any reason there shall not be enough vol-
untary enlistments to keep the reserve battalions
at the prescribed strength, a sufficient number of
the unorganized militia shall be drafted into the
service of the United States to maintain each of such
battalions at the proper strength.” ,

Huddleston declared that the word “called” had
been in the’ earlier draft of the bill, but that on
March 22d it had been changed in secret confer-
ence to “drafted.” On the following day (March
23d) the matter had been brought up by Represen-
tative Miller of Minnesota, who asked if the word
“ordered” could not be substituted. Representative
Hay, of Virginia, the sponsor for the bill, there-
upon declared that the word “ordered” did not have
the legal signiﬁcance of the word “drafted.” On
Miller’s further question if the word “called” might
not be substituted, Hay replied that the same objec-
tion held. “He (the president)”, said Hay, “may
call Volunteers into the service of the United States,
but this language is necessary in order that they
may cease to be militia.”

On the day (August 25th) when Huddleston intro-
duced his repeal resolution, Hay again took the
ﬂoor. In -reply to Huddleston’s charges, he said:

“He (Huddleston) bases his criticism on the fact
that the word ‘call’ was stricken out and the word
‘draft’ substituted in conference. I do not now
recollect whether that is true or not, but what is
the difference between the President being author-
ized to call men out and to draft them? There is
no difference, so far as the President is concerned.”
Huddleston’s resolution was defeated.

  

