THE REGISTRATION AREA.

The term “registration area,” which is frequently
found in statistical matter, means that part of the
United States in which the laws requiring the
registration of births and deaths are sufficiently
comprehensive and rigorous to insure approxi-
mately correct ﬁgures. It consists of California,
Colorado, Connecticut, District of Columbia, In-
diana, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan,
Minnesota, Montana, New Hampshire, New Jersey,
New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Utah,
Vermont, Washington, Wisconsin, the municipalities
of 1,000 and more population in North Carolina, and
43 cities in non-registration States. It contained, on
July 1, 1910, 53,843,896 population. or 58.3 per cent.
of the total for the United States.

