THE ADAMSON ACT.

The eight-hour law for railway trainmen, known

as the Adamson Act, was approved by the President
/on Sept. 3 (and again on Sept. 5, the former date
falling on a Sunday), 1916. It is in four sections.

The ﬁrst section declares that after Jan. 1, 1917, ’

eight hours shall be deemed a day’s work for the
purpose of reckoning compensation for all employes
engaged in train operation on all interstate railroads
(electric street and inter-urban railroads are ex-
cepted), including switching and terminal companies.

The second section provides that the President
shall appoint a commission of three to observe the
operation and effects of the law during a period of
not less than six months nor more than nine months,
and to report within thirty days thereafter to the
President and Congress. A sum of $25,000 is appro-

priated for expenses.
‘ The third section forbids, during the maximum ‘

time mentioned above, the reduction of the wages of
the employes below the present standard, and or-
dains the payment of overtime at regular rates.

The fourth section provides for a ﬁne of not less
than $100 nor more than $1,000, or‘ imprisonment
or both, for violations. .,

The commissioners appointed were Major-General
George W‘. Goethals, Elmer E. Clark, of the Inter-
state Commerce Commission, and George Rublee, of
the Trade Commission. :

NEW FEDERAL COMPENSATION LAW.

The Federal Compensation law, superseding the
law of 1908, was signed by the President Sept. 7,
1916. The bill was prepared by the collaboration
of the American Association for Labor Legislation
and the United States Bureau of Labor Statistics.
It extends the provisions of the former act to all
employes of the United States suffering injuries
while in the performance of their duties. It pro-

vides for beneﬁts on a basis of two-thirds of the .

injured employe’s. wages, payments continuing as

long as the disability lasts. Partial disability is ’

compensated on the basis of the wage loss resulting
from the injury. Death beneﬁts to a widow cease
only on her death or remarriage and to children on
their attaining the age of 18, though they may con-
tinue’beyond this date if incapacitated from earning
a living. Other beneﬁciaries are to be provided for
in the absence of the foregoing or subject to their
prior rights.

