AGAINST JUDICIAL USURPATION.

In the United States Senate, on January 8, 1917,
Senator Robert L. Owen of Oklahoma, introduced a

--joint resolution forbidding Federal judges to declare

any act of Congress unconstitutional on penalty of
removal from office.

A similar proposition, though relating only to a

speciﬁc measure, was included by Representative
Victor L. Berger, in 1911, in his Old Age Pensions
bill. The section read:
‘ “Section 11. That in accord with paragraph two,
section two, Article III of the Constitution, and of
the precedent established by the act passed over the
President's veto March 27, 1868, the exercise of juris-
diction by any ofthe Federal courts upon the valid-
ity of this act is hereby expressly forbidden.”

 

