LOW BIRTH RATE’ AMONG COLLEGE GRADUATES. ‘'1,

In a statement published in August, 1915, Ros-
well H. Johnson, professor of biology of the Uni—
versity of Pittsburgh, gives the results of his
researches regarding the marriage and birth rate
among college Women. The investigations included
the marriage records of the alumnae of Wellesley,
Bryn Mawr, Smith, Vassar, Mount Holyoke and Wil-
son. The number of marriages among graduates of
these institutions was found to reach an average
of‘only 39 per cent. of the total.

Prof. Johnson ﬁnds that from all college girls
there is contributed to the race only four—fifths of
a child per capita, while among honor students per
capita the rate amounts to only one—fifth of a child.

“The number of children,” he says, “which are
necessary to maintain a stationary population 1
from these groups should be about 3.7 per woman ‘
student. Among the honor students only about 35
.per cent. marry, and from these only two-tenths of
a child is contributed for duplication of their kind.
There are three causes for this abnormal low birth
rate: First, lack of co-education; second, failure of
their education to make them desirous of having
a home of their own, and third, the excessive limita-
tion of students’ opportunities for social life.”

