father clause” in various Southern State constitu-
tions.‘ The decision upheld the conviction of two
Oklahoma election officials Who denied Negroes the
right to vote in a Congressional election and
awarded three Maryland Negroes damages from
election officials in Annapolis who refused to regis-
ter them. - .

The decision was unanimous and was read by

the Chief Justice, a native of the South andia:

former Confederate soldier. The court held that
these restrictions were directly in violation of the
Fifteenth Amendment. In ﬁxing a literary standard
and then granting suffrage to illiterates who them-
selves, or whose ancestors, were entitled to vote
on January 1, 1866, the Oklahoma amendment, ac-

cording to the decision, attempted to circumvent

the plain provisions of: the Federal amendment.
The Annapolis ordinance made a like discrimina-
tion. “Certainly,” reads the decision, “it cannot be
said that there was any peculiar necromancy in
the time named which engendered attributes af-
fecting the qualiﬁcation to vote which could not
exist at another and different period unless the
Fifteenth Amendment was in view.” It was the
ﬁrst time that the “grandfather clause” or any of
its variants had come before the Supreme Court.‘

