THE IMMIGRANT AND THE FARM.

_The fact that the overwhelming majority of
immigrants congregate in the cities and that only
a small part even of those who have been farm.
workers in Europe move to the farm districts of
the United States is treated by Prof. Jeremiah W.-
Jenks, in the following excerpts from an article-
syndicated by the National Editorial Service in the
summer of 1915:

Even immigrants with agricultural training, in-
stead of going to the great farming States of the
Union, persist in swelling our urban populations,

~in stagnating in our already congested cities and

in increasing thenumbers of out—of-works, thus.
making more acute sporadic conditions of unem-

. ployment in_ our industrial centers. Only 20,174, or

5 per cent., of the foreign—born males, 21 years of
ageand over, living in Massachusetts in 1910 were
to be found in the rural districts, notwithstanding
the fact that 12 per cent. of the total immigration
to that State from 1899 to 1910 were speciﬁcally
mentioned as farmers and farm laborers. In 1914
23,389 farmers and farm laborers were destined to
Massachusetts, but, judging from past ﬁgures, it is
extremely doubtful whether any appreciable portion
of these agriculturists will ever reach the country
districts. ‘

\ Slightly less than 100,000 immigrants, or only
about 8.3 per cent. out of a total immigration of
1,218,488 in 1914, "were headed towards the great
farming States .of Alabama, Arizona, Arkansas,
Florida, Idaho, Iowa, Kansas, Minnesota, Missouri,
Nebraska, North and South Dakota, Texas, Wis-
consin and Wyoming, while the four great indus-
trial States, New York, Pennsylvania, Massachusetts
and Illinois, shared between them the enormous
number of 700,000, or nearly 60 per cent. of the
total immigration to this country in that year. Of

the 13,515,886 foreign-born found‘ in the United

States in 1910 these four States contained 6,454,944,
or 47 per cent., clear proof that our incoming im-
migrants add to our overcrowded cities and do not,
to any measureable extent, reach the farm. -

In 1890, 38.2 per cent. of our foreign-born were

’ to be found in rural districts; in 1900, 33.2 per cent.;

and.in 1910 the percentage had fallen to 27.8._ Only
223,731 more foreign-born were to be found in the
country districts in 1910 than in 1890,,while the num-
ber of foreign—born in the cities increased about
4,000,000 during the same period.

It would seem from these ﬁgures as if there was

  

