THE SPREAD OF PROHIBITION.

Prohibition was adopted in 1914 in Arizona,
Colorado, Oregon, Virginia, and Washington, and in
1915 by Alabama, Arkansas, Idaho, Iowa and South
Carolina. Other prohibition States are Kansas,
Maine, Oklahoma, Georgia, Mississippi, North Caro-
lina, Tennessee, W. Virginia and North Dakota.

The Alabama law, which was passed over the
governor’s veto, went into effect July 1, 1915. The
Florida law of the same year was vetoed. The South
Carolina law was adopted at the polls September
14, 1915, and became effective January 1, 1916. The
Idaho law is a statutory enactment. Iowa became

.virtually a prohibition State through the repeal of

the mulct law (1915).

Prohibition, in oneform or another, was an issue
in 1916 in thirteen States and one Territory.

In Alaska, Michigan, Montana, Nebraska and South
Dakota prohibition was adopted at the polls. In,
California two amendments, one providing for par-
tial prohibition in 1918 and the other absolute pro-
hibition in 1920, were defeated. In Florida a “dry”
Legislature was elected. In South Dakota a local
option, measure favored by the “wets” was defeated
at the polls. In Utah a “dry” governor was elected.
In Colorado an amendment liberalizing the present

I prohibition section of the constitution was defeated

at the polls. In Arkansas the voters defeated a
measure substituting a local option measure for the
present prohibition section of the constitution. In
Oregon the voters defeated the so-called “brewers’
bill” and adopted instead the so-called “bone-dry”
amendment to the constitution. In Maryland, unde-r
local option prohibition was enacted in'a number of
counties and cities but defeated in Baltimore. In
Illinois the issue was prominent in the election of
members of the Legislature.

;In 23 States there is now state-wide prohibition.

In States that have county option there are many

“dry” counties. Out of a total of 2,543 counties in
the nation, all but 355 are now said to be “dry.”
The oldest prohibition State is Maine, whose law
was enacted in 1851. Kansas came second in 1880
and North Dakota third in 1889.

