INTRODUCTION.

This is the third edition of the Almanac and
the nineteenth of the Arsenal of Facts. Much new
material has been added in this issue, and a special
effort has been made to bring each statement or
statistical table.down to the very latest date. In
certain cases preliminary ﬁgures———both official and
unofficial—have been used, which may or may not
be subsequently altered. As was explained in the
previous issue, it is often impossible to obtain late
revisions of statistical matter. An inquiry and
report on a particular subject may be made, and
never followed .up with a subsequent report. In
other cases, such as some of the census investiga-
tions, a period of ten years must elapse before new
ﬁgures are obtainable. What has been attempted
here is a revision of all material to include the
latest available information. ,

Two new summaries have been especially pre-
pared for this issue. One condenses the noteworthy
and valuable report known as Public Health Bulletin
No. 76, and the other the report of the Illinois
Senate Committee on Vice. In the latter will be
found a strong reiteration of the argument that
vice is chiefly the product of poverty.

The long summary of the Rural Credits Law,
published by the Agricultural Department, is deemed
of sufficient importance to our readers‘ to warrant
its inclusion. Since, however, the good faith of

‘the law is questioned, a criticism of the measure,

written by Patrick S. Nagle, is also included.
Many minor additions and innumerable changes
will be found throughout the volume. Particular
attention may be called to the brief abstract of
Prof. W. I. King’s remarkable study of the national
income; the detailed ﬁgures on the appropriations
of the recent congress; the list——along with several
abstracts—of the more important measures passed
by that body; the new ﬁgures on mining casualties
and war costs; the new names in the list of heads
of government; the new table of corporation pen-
sions, and the preliminary ﬁgures on railway earn-
ings. It is hoped that the present issue will be
found the completest and most useful edition so
far of the Almanac and Arsenal of Facts. . e
