SOCIALISM AND DEMOCRACY.

Democracy bears very much the same relation to
Socialism that the circulation of the blood bears
to the human body. Without democracy Socialism
becomes incapable of performing‘ its functions, just
as the organs, of the body become incapable of per-
forming their functions Without the circulation of
the blood. '

Socialism is deﬁned as: “The collective owner-

ship and democratic managzjement of things collec—_

tively used.” Under this deﬁnition Socialism i‘ep1'e~
seiits an established ‘form of society in which its
members control and direct, in their col‘lective

capacity, the management of its social, political and

economic affairs.

The status of such a society then must neces~
sarily be a true reﬂex of the degree and character
of the democracy applied to the workings of the
organization.

Democracy is a term used to represent the medium‘
through which the primal needs and requirements
of society are expressed and through which the
majority give voice to their preference of different
propositions that shall become the law. governing:
and regulating'_ their conduct as citizens of the
commonwealth.

Socialism. as a system of government to be applied
to society, is not a deﬁnite, inﬂexible program. But
on the other hand, it is a program of the greatest
ﬂexibility, Varying to accommodate the inﬂux of
new concepts that are designed to shape its ends
to a’ definite purpose.

It is here that the inseparable relationship be-
tween Socialism and democracy is so clearly maiii—
fested. No one can fail to appreciate the import-
ance that Socialism attaches to the expressions of
an intelligent democracy.

Just as the condition of the blood is revealed in
the appearance of the body,‘ so are the degree and
character of democracy manifested in the organic-
structure of the Socialist organization in which it
functions. The potency of democracy is determined
by the degree of experience and intelligence of
those from which it emanates, and it.s vitality, or‘
feebleness is indelibly impressed upon the Socialist
organization. .
/ Socialism is the only source from which the ideals‘
of the new democracy can be evolved for it is the-

“only organization in which democracy becomes a
/ living reality instead of a theoretic creed,

 

 

 

 

