Disease Caused by Fatigue.

Excessive fatigue is also a fertile cause of disease.
Long hours, the piecework system, the increasing

use of machine methods and the setting of workers"

at tasks beyond their strength, bring exhaustion,
which in turn breeds illness. In spite of the move-

ment for the shorter workday and of recent favor- -

able court decisions on laws limiting the hours of
women, a large proportion of wage-earners are still
working 10 or more hours per day for a seven-day
week. The latest data of the Bureau of Labor
show.that in the iron and steel industry 62.6 per
cent. of the blast-furnace workers are still held to
84 hours’ labor per week. Further examples are
given, of excessively long workdays. .

The evil effect of the piecework system and of
working at tasks beyond one’s strength in a par-
ticular industry is shown by a report of examina-
tions made upon shovelers in the zinc mines of
Joplin, Mo., by Dr. A. J. Lanza:

“They had shoveled from two to six years; some
had started when 18 or 19 years of age. Now they
could shovel only 35 or 40 cans, where formerly
they could shovel 60 to 70 and upward. Hard,
constant work had broken these men down, so that
at the ages of 22 to 30 they were already on the
down grade * " ‘. Working thus at their full
earning capacity day in and day out, it is not sur-
prising that with the added exposure to rock dust
these men should contract tuberculosis to an exces-
sive -degree. Especially must this be true when they
start in while under age and before their bodies
have fully developed.”

‘The increasingstrain due to the introduction of
machine methods and to speeding-up practices is
also a potent cause of break-down and illness.

