NATIONAL DEBTS OF THE WORLD.

According to a statement issued by the Depart-
ment of Commerce in Washington, the national debts
of the world aggregated in 1913 the enormous sum
of $42,000,000,000. They showed an increase of 20
per cent, in 10 years and of 100 per cent. in 40
years. The annual charges (interest, etc.) on these
debts amounted to $1,732,000,000, which was an aver-
age of slightly more than 4 per cent.

No later ﬁgures are yet obtainable. The European
war has, of course, vastly increased the debts of
the warring nations, as shown in the table on a
previous page. '

In many cases, especially among nations having
the best_credit, the interest rates were lower than
4 per cent., but with the weaker nations the rates
were much higher. The average rate paid by the
United States ranged from 2 to 4 per cent.; in Great
Britain it was from 2% to 2% per cent.; in Russia
from 2 to 6 per cent.; in Japan from 4 to 5; in the
German Empire from 3 to 4; in China from 4 to
5; in Nicaragua 6; in Panama 7; in Ecuador from
4 to 10; in Honduras from 5 to 10. Of course, these
rates do not accurately indicate what the loans cost
the governments, inasmuch, as in many cases, es-
pecially with countries of weak credit, the securi-
ties were sold at less than par. '

