\ RECENT INCREASES IN FARM VALUES. ,\

Farm land values are increasing almost by leaps
and bounds, according to ﬁgures made public by the
Department of Agriculture on April 9, 1916. Values
for the United States, taken as a whole, increased
25.7 per cent. in the last four years and 11.5 per
cent. between 1915 and 1916. The figures are based
upon reports from the department’s ﬁeld agents.
The value of farm lands without improvements is
estimated at $45.50 per acre, compared with $40.85
a year ago; $40.31 two years ago; $38.10 tliree years
ago, and $36.23 four years ago. 0

Increases have ‘been general with one or two
notable exceptions in the Northwest. The excep-
tiona} increases of the last year are attributed to
thepreaction in the South following the temporary
depression of the year before, and to the stimulws
of war prices, particularly of grain.

FOREST FIRES, 1915.

Forest ﬁres burned over not quite 300,000 acres
of National Forest land in 1915, according to official
reports given out by the Interior Department on
March 24,1916. Out of a total of 6,324 ﬁres, 346, or
51/2 per cent., did damage to the amount of $100 or
more. i
T The timber loss was $190,000. Over 87 per cent. of
this loss occurred in the States of Oregon, Wash-
ington and Idaho, while more than 72 per cent. was
in Oregon alone. Besides the timber loss, ﬁres de-
stroyed reproduction, or young tree growth, of an
estimated value of $160,000. 1

