Unhealthful Conditions of Living.

The effect of inadequate diet, bad housing and
generally unfavorable environment in causing dis-
ease is treated at some length. Low wages and
high food prices combine to doom the average wage-
earner’s family to chronic underfeeding. “It is
clearly evident,” say the authors, “that the tendency
during the period 1900-13 has been toward an im-
poverishment of the diet of families with low
incomes.” Bad housing, especially when connected
with overcrowding of population, is a proliﬁc source
of disease. Tuberculosis has been found to be
particularly an incident of bad housing conditions.
As Dr. Osler expresses it, it is a “house disease.”
A survey of the Washington street district in New
York City showed that 57 per cent. of the families
lived in two rooms, and 26 per cent. in three rooms,
many of these families having lodgers-. The death
rate from tuberculosis in this district was found
to be about four times the rate generally prevalent.
Other studiesof New York life reveal even worse
conditions.

