The much xheralded farmers’ rural credit bill is
now the law of the land. It was signed by the
President on July 17, 1916. Hip, hip, hurrah for
the Democratic party, Woodrow Wilson, Robert L.
Owen, T. P. Gore, Scott Ferris et a1.! No more
shall the 120,000 tenant farmers of Oklahoma live
in “pole pen” and one-room shacks with a “leanto.”
No more saleratus biscuit, sorghum molasses and
alkali water for the tenant farmer——it is beefsteak
and pork chops now. The act is known as public
No. 158»

This act covers twenty-nine pages of closely
printed matter. It is involved, intricate, mislead-
ing and_ crooked. Like all capitalist measures pur-
porting to be for the relief of the working class,
the doors are left wide open for hostile judicial
construction. In the caption is one naked truth;
it says the bill was passed “to create standard
forms of investments based upon farm mortgages.”
The billions of dollars made by American capital-
ists in the last two years, selling munitions and
supplies, is seeking a ﬁeld for investment, and farm
bonds at 6 per cent. look good to them. ‘The
the farm mortgage “standard-
ized” like a United States bond before he puts
out his money. ’

Will this so-called “Federal Farm Loan Act”
help the tenant farmer? Not in the least, He has
no land to mortgage; he has no assets—-and the
probability is he never will have under the exist-
ing or er. “For whosoever hath, to him shall be
given, and he shall have more abundance, but who-
soever hath not, from him, shall be taken away
even that he hath not.” \

_ Will it not help the mortgaged farmer, who owns
and occupies his own land? It will not. It is un-
workable. It will take ﬁve or six years to show
that it is unworkable, and then there will be an-
other period of investigation, and before any relief
can be had the small farmer will be closed out and
marching in the ranks of the tenant farmer. The

 

 

 

  

