spies in the employ of the company.

“Is the company always in a state of prepared-
ness for any industrial Warfare that might spring
up?” ‘asked Mr. Walsh, “such as having‘"men and
arms and clubs on hand?’’

“We are always prepared for anything the other
fellow is getting ready for, I can assure you,” Mr.
Atterbury replied. ,

“HoW many riﬂes do you keep on hand?”

“I don’t know that we keep any, but we have
everything that is legal that is necessary to keep
on hand to protect the running of our trains.”

“Shouldn’t the control of armed forces, in your
opinion, rest with the State?” Mr. Walsh asked.

