MORGAN’S RECOMPENSE. ~
From a report of the Commissioner of Corporations
in Sen. Doc. 301, 62nd Congress. 2d Session.

When the steel trust was organized in 1901 the
value of all the tangible assets acquired by it was
$682,000,000. This property was capitalizedfor the
enormous total of $1,402,864,817, the capitalization

being more than half water and /exceeding the

actual value of the property by $720,846,817. The
syndicate which put through this enormous deal
was managed by J. P. Morgan. This syndicate‘
provided about $28,000,000 in cash to swing the
deal, and for this cash consideration, plus its un-
derwriting services, it received from the steel cor-
poration 1,300,000 shares of its stock, having an
aggregate par value of $130,000,000. This stock
realized approximately $90,500,000, leaving as proﬁt
to the syndicate, over and above its $28,000,000
cash expenditure, a net sum of $62,500,000. Of this
sum one-ﬁfth, or $12,500,000, went to Morgan for

