HOW THE PRICE OF COFFEE WAS RAISED.
(From Pear‘son’s Magazine, October, 1911.)

In December, 1908, the price of No. 7 Rio coffee
in New York was 61/2 cents a pound. In January,
1911, the same grade of coffee in the same market
sold at 131-3 cents a pound, an increase in two
years of more than 100 per cent. This rate was
caused by an arrangement entered into by the
Brazilian government and a group of ﬁnancial ban-
dits, of which J. P. Morgan & Co. are the American
representatives, wherebythe coffee crop of Brazil
is cornered and held out of the market so as to
enable this combination to regulate the price of
cotfee throughout the world. After the formation
of the combination the Brazilian government sent
its agents throughout the coffee districts destroying
growing trees so as to keep down the supply. The
government also has a law limiting: the export of

 

 

  
  
  

 

 

 

 

 

  

