cial session of Congress, summer of 1911, by the
Stanley Committee, and Roosevelt testiﬁed to his
own immaculate honesty in the matter. Later he
further justiﬁed himself in an article in the Outlook
(New, York), On October 26, 1911, however, the
Government, in its complaint ﬁled against the steel
trust, declared that the magnates had “misled”
Roosevelt, and that by “hammering the Tennessee
stock” and “threatening a general ﬁnancial calamity”

 

 

 

 

  

 

