OTHER FACTORS.

This is not, however, the whole problem. There
were miscellaneous expenses, reaching the enormous
total of nearly two billions. If this item were purely
a labor charge, it would, of course, in an attempt
to determine the value of the worker’s toil, have to
be deducted from the total value. It happens, how-
ever, that a large part of miscellaneous expenses
is a capital charge—that is, a toll which capitalism
takes out of the production. The classiﬁcation of
the various entries under this heading in the 1904
census showed that no less than 86 per cent. of this
expense was a capital charge-——rent of offices, rent
of land, insurance and the like. It was a charge

on the individual employer, of course; but it was

a capital charge and not a labor charge. It was the
toll of the money-lender, the real estate owner, per-
haps the owner of the building, the machinery manu-
facturer, the lawyer, the politician, the grafter and
the Lord knows what. However great was this toll,
it was not chargeable to labor. — '

The aid in production that was given by the
790,267 salaried employees cannot be determined.
A certain amount of superintendence, designing,
inventing, planning and clerical work is, of course,
absolutely essential in production. A great many
high salaries, on the other hand, are merely in-
stances of disguised proﬁts, and therefore a part
of the toll of capital. It may be a fair guess that
two-thirds of these salaried employees, —or 526,844,
rendered actual aid in producing values, and that
they received about one-half of the total salary
expense, or $469,287,500, the other one—third of the
salaried persons‘ getting the other one—half of the
total.

