If we ‘make these deductions, reducing the
amount for legitimate miscellaneous expenses to
14 per cent. of the total given, we shall have a
total net proﬁt of $7,985,471,660, produced by a

total of 7,141,900 wage-earning workers and their -

salaried auxiliaries, an average of, $1,118, each.
These persons received $545. each, or 48.8 per cent.
The other 51.2 per cent. went to capital in some of
its various forms.

The result is conjectural only. The same basic
ﬁgures may be reviewed in many ways, giving the
worker’s share as anywhere from 45 to 52 per cent.
In some industries the value added by manufacture
is very low; in Henry Ford’s automobile factory

it is very high. -. For the whole factory production’

of the nation it is safe to say that capital, in one
or another of its many forms, “draws down” from
50 to 55 per cent. of What the working class pro-
duces. ” A

