paid were $4,079,332,000, against $3,427,038,000
in 1909, an increase of 19 per cent. The average
weekly wages (including those of women and chil-
dren) were in 1914, $11.15; in 1909, $9.96; an in-
crease of 11.8 per cent. The average increase in
food prices between 1909 and 1914 was, according
to Bulletin 197 of the Federal Bureau of Labor
Statistics, 16.1 per cent.

