Washington. . . . . . .June 13 California. . . . . . .August 10'
Minnesota. . . . . . . . .June 26 Colorado. . . . . . . .August 12
Massachusetts. . . . . .July 1 Arkansas . . . . . . .March, 1915

~ Kansas . . . . . . . . .May 22, 1915

Michigan, New York and Idaho have also taken
preliminary steps in the same direction.

The laws of 1913 are in the main alike. In Utah
only females are included. All the others include
minors—under 18 in Oregon, Washington, Massa-
chusetts, Nebraska, California and Colorado, under
21 in Minnesota and Wisconsin.

All industries are covered in all the States except
Colorado. All the States, except Utah and Wiscon-
sin, create a commission to administer the law. In
Utah the Labor Commissioner administers it, and
in Wisconsin the Industrial Commission. .

The eight commissions are authorized to deter-
mine" the wage needful for a living. The Cali-
fornia, Oregon and Wisconsin commissions have
also the power to determine maximum hours and
conditions of labor. All the commissions may
subpoena Witnesses, administer oaths and examine
books. In California and Wisconsin they may also
enter premises. In Massachusetts, Minnesota, Ne-
braska, Oregon and Wisconsin the commissions
(and in Utah the Labor Commissioner) have au-
thority to enforce all their decisions, while in Cali-
fornia and Washington they may enforce only
wage decisions.

The Arkansasstatute became effective on its
passage. It applies to. females working in any
manufacturing, mechanical or mercantile establish-
ment, laundry or express or transportation com-
pany. Hours are restricted to nine per day and 54
per week. The minimum wage is ﬁxed by law at
not less than $1.25 per day for female workers of
six months’ experience, with a minimum of $1 per
day for inexperienced workers. Proportionate re-
ductions for a shorter workday are permitted.

The Kansas law creates a commission to establish
standards of wages, hours and conditions for women

 

