CAMPAIGN AGAINST UNEMPLOYMENT.

The American Association for Labor Legislation
discussed the problem of unemployment at its
national conference in New York, Feb. 27-28, 1914.
Despite the ,great diversity of viewpoints presented,
there was general agreement on ﬁve main needs:

‘1. The necessity for accurate labor market sta-
tistics. \ .

2. The necessity for a widespread system of
efficient labor exchanges.

3 The necessity for regularizing business, so as
to eliminate seasonal unemployment.

4.. The necessity for vocational training and
guidance. -

5. The necessity for unemployment insurance.

The second national conference was held at Phila-
delphia Dec. 28-29, 1914. Reports were made that six
legislatures had made provision for public employ-
ment exchanges and that a number of cities had
set up municipal bureaus. -

The “Unemployment Survey,” reviewing the con-
ditions of 1914-15 and recommending lines of action,
was issued in November, 1915.

DNEMPLOYMENT INSURANCE.

Three nations—Great Britain, Denmark and Nor-
way—have enacted unemployment insurance laws.

\ The Norwegian system is said to have failed. (The

Danish system has been in operation since 1907 and
has been successful. It is a scheme of voluntary
insurance by workingmen’s societies, under State
regulation and with both State and community sub-‘

sidies to the unemployment funds. On April 1, -1915,’

there were 57 “funds,” or societies maintaining un-
employment insurance, with 139,505 members. For
the ﬁscal year 1913-14 the members paid in 51 per
cent. of the income, the State 30 and the communi-
ties 14 per cent. For the ﬁscal year 1914-15 the total
income was $871,585, the unemployment beneﬁts and
the cost of administration were $825,046. '

Great Britain’s insurance system is compulsory.

It dates from July 15, 1912, though beneﬁts have

been paid only since Jan. 15, 1913. It insures all
workers above 16 in the building trades, in machine
manufacturing, ship and wagon building, iron mould-
ing and saw-milling. It establishes a national em-
ployment fund, with a national system of labor ex-
changes. Five cents a. week is paid by each_ em-
ployee, another ﬁve cents by his employer, and the
Government adds a subsidy equal to one-third of

