COMPENSATION FOR ACCIDENTS. 1

The United States was the last nation of any im-
portance to take up the question of compensating

workmen for accidents.

The movement had begun

in Germany by thevpassage of a law on June 15,
1883, and by 1909 had spread all over Europe, to
Australia, New Zealand, Canada and South Africa.
At that time, however, not a single State in the.

Union had such a law among its statutes.

On May 30, 1908, a Federal act making compen-
sation for the death or injury of Government arti-
sans and laborers was approved, but the States still
hung back; All at once, beginning with 1911, State
measures began to be enacted, and at this time
thirty—ﬁve States and Territories have such laws.

Maryland was the first State to pass a measure
which, though it was greatly restricted, could rea-
sonably be called a workmen’s compensation law.
The act was in effect only from July 1, 1902, to
April 28, 1904, when it was declared unconstitu-

tional.
