CAUSES OF WIFE DESERTION.

Judge Henry Neil, father of the Mothers’ Pension,
has spent many months investigating the causes of
wife desertion. During his work he crossed the
continent seven. times and stopped in almost every
city in the country.

Low wages to -workingmen he classes as the
fundamental cause. Eight other causes, all result-
ing from insufficient income, are as follows:

Unemployment—Changing a hard—working man
into a discouraged loafer.

Bad housing—Dwe1lings so small that the man
can ﬁnd no room for‘his leisure hours and is forced
to go out except when sleeping or eating.

Whiskey———Usual1y resorted to as a result of the
preceding causes.

Arrest and imprisonment of low-paid workers on
charges of failure to support families.

Interference of charity workers in the affairs of
low-paid workmen.

Feeling of disgrace because the worker has had
to accept charity.

Prison and military or naval experiences which
taught habits unﬁtting a man for home life.

Conduct of the wife.

Among well paid workmen, according to Judge
Neil, desertions are few; they increase as wages
go down. .

