THE APPEAL ALMANAC AND

The Commons-Harriman Report.

The report of Prof. John R. Commons and Mrs.
Florence J. Harriman (signed also, with reserva-
tions, by Commissioners Weinstock, Ballard and
Aishton) dissents from all the ﬁndings and recom-
mendations of the Staff report, “because they have
not the criticism of employers, employees and others
affected by them,” and therefore lack assurance of
accuracy. This report is based on the thesis that
the system of labor legislation in the United States
has broken down and that what is needed is not
new laws, but new machinery for investigation,
legislation and administration. Governments alone,
says the report, cannot be looked to for remedying
evil conditions. The greatest improvements to
come are to be expected through co-operation with
government of such voluntary organizations as em-
ployers’ associations, labor unions and farmers’
societies.

Accordingly the report develops an elaborate and
detailed plan of a Federal commission, as well as
State commissions, for the administration of all
labor laws. All bureaus dealing in any way with
industrial conditions are to be placed under the
direction_of such commission or commissions. Each
commission is to consist of three members, ap-
pointed by the governor (by the President in the
case of the Federal commission) to serve for six
years, except that the ﬁrst appointees shall be
named for various terms in order that no two shall
retire at the same time. Advisory councils are
also provided for. The report is somewhat vague
as to the degree of the commissions’ powers. The
whole scheme is a curious mixture of Jeffersonian
democracy and Prussian bureaucracy. s

A note by Commissioner Weinstock dissents from
a statement in the Commons-Harriman report that
new restrictions on immigration should be enacted.
The Commissioner asserts that we already have
abundant immigration laws and that immigration is
a good instead of an evil.

‘ The Employers’ Report.

As members of the Commission appointed to
represent the employers, Messrs. Weinstock, Ballard
and Aishton join in a report in which they recite
the difficulties that prevent the full recognition

of the unions by the employing class. They dis-~

sent from the recommendation in the Commons-
Harriman report that the secondary boycott be
legalized and also dissent from the proposed limita-
tion of governmental inquiry regarding labor dis-

 

 

 

