THE RACES OF MANKIND.

Controversy about race is endless and expresses
itself often in extreme ‘diversities of opinion. From
the school that declares “race is nothing,” there is
a regular gradation of view up to that which de-
clares that “race is everything.” Much of this
controversy, however, is concerned not with race
but with groups or families or stocks of the same
race. Much of it, moreover, is concerned with mental
rather than with physical differences or re- -
semblances.

All observers agree that there are marked
physical differences among men, that certain types
are persistent, and that the strongly marked types
are localized in various sections of the earth. Many
attempts at scientiﬁc classiﬁcation have been made.
Some are based on distribution (or localization),
others on the shape of the top or back of the skull,
still others on the color of the skin, or the straight-
ness or waviness of the hair, and yet others on
language. The language test has generally been
given up, and in general the test of craniology, or
skull shape.

The arrangement of Prof. Amos W.‘ Butler, based
largely on Blumenthal and Huxley, is given below.
It classiﬁes mankind into five main races, with
13 branches, 35 “stocks” and uncounted groups.
The word “peoples” is used for a number of groups.
For instance, the German and French groups be-
long to the Indo-Germanic peoples, to the Aryac or
Aryan stock, and to the North Mediterranean
branch of the European race. Huxley’s distinction
between the “fair whites” of North Europe and
the “dark whites” of South Europe is not shown in
the table. The “dark whites” are supposed to be
a blend of the North.Mcditcrranean and the South
Mediterranean branches.

