OTHER CORPORATION PENSIONS.

The U. S. Steel Corporation dedicated $8,000,000
for a fund with which to pension superannuated
and disabled employes. This fund has been con-
solidated with the $4,000,000 fund created by Andrew
Carnegie after he sold out his holdings in the
Carriegie Steel Company to the U. S. Steel Corpora-

7 tion. The fund is known as “The United States

Steel and Carnegie Pension Fund.” 7

The Western Union Telegraph Company, on Janu-
ary 1, 1913, established a Plan for Employees’ Pen-
sions, Disability Benefits and Insurance, setting
aside a fund of $1,000,000 for the purpose. Pensions
are classiﬁed according to age and length of ser-
vice. The minimum pension is $20 per month, except
when otherwise directed. In cases of disability from
sickness, full pay and half pay are allowed for vari-
ous periods, depending upon length of service; pro-
vision is also made for disability resulting from
accidents and for life insurance beneﬁts, the amount
of insurance depending upon length of service.

July 31, 1916, Swift & Co., the packers, of Chicago,
announced a ‘$2,000,000 pension plan for employes,

‘including those in the main plants there and in

branch houses all over the country.
A notable feature is that -~employes do not con-

tribute to the fund. Officials estimated that $400,-

000 a year, in addition to the income of the $2,000,000
initiatory fund, will be required to conduct, the
system. About 28,000 men and women came under
the plan on the following day when it went into

' operation.

Men in the employ of the company twenty-ﬁve
years, who have reached the age of sixty, may be
pensioned. When they reach .the age of sixty-ﬁve,
they must retire on pension. Women’s ages are
ﬁxed at ﬁve years less. No pension will be less
than $240 per year and none over $5,000 a year.

